{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "You check the forecast: “30% chance of rain.” That’s probability talk guiding a real choice—bring an umbrella, wear waterproof shoes, or risk it and travel lighter.",
      "title": "The “Chance of Rain” Check"
    },
    {
      "text": "At the grocery store, you pick the “family pack” because you’ll probably use it before it expires. You’re quietly weighing odds: how likely you’ll cook, snack, or eat out this week.",
      "title": "Grocery Shopping & Food Waste"
    },
    {
      "text": "Driving a different route because “traffic is usually bad at 5”? That’s probability from experience. You’re betting on the route with better odds of getting you there on time.",
      "title": "Commuting and Choosing Routes"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you buy a phone warranty, you’re asking: “What are the chances it breaks, and would I regret the cost?” That’s probability thinking turning uncertainty into a money decision.",
      "title": "Warranties and Big Purchases"
    },
    {
      "text": "Card games, dice, and board games are packed with probability moments. Deciding whether to roll again, draw another card, or play it safe is basically a live odds-and-risk conversation.",
      "title": "Game Night Decisions"
    },
    {
      "text": "That “skip the line” pass at an amusement park? You’re paying to reduce the probability of wasting time. Same idea when you arrive early at the airport to avoid the risk of missing a flight.",
      "title": "Lines, Delays, and Time Buffers"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you see a headline and think, “How likely is that, really?” you’re using probability as a skepticism filter—especially with health claims, miracle products, or viral “facts.”",
      "title": "News, Rumors, and “Is This True?”"
    },
    {
      "text": "A recruiter saying “We usually hire 1 out of 20 applicants” is probability in career form. You plan your applications like a pipeline because each one has uncertain odds.",
      "title": "Job Searching and Interviews"
    },
    {
      "text": "Doctors talk about risks like side effects or screening accuracy. Even if the numbers aren’t perfect, probability helps you compare options and choose what feels worth it for you.",
      "title": "Health Choices and Medical Risks"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you diversify investments, you’re basically saying, “I don’t want my future tied to one roll of the dice.” Probability shows up anytime you spread risk across different options.",
      "title": "Money, Investing, and Risk"
    },
    {
      "text": "Dating and friendships involve uncertainty too: you choose where to meet people, how often to reach out, and what signals to trust—raising the odds of a good connection over time.",
      "title": "Relationships and Social Plans"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coaches and players think in odds: take the safe points or go for the risky play? Even fans do it—“Do we go for it on 4th down?” Probability is hiding in the strategy talk.",
      "title": "Sports Strategy and “Go for It?”"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "You notice eggs cost more this week. Maybe a flu hit hens (less supply) or everyone’s baking for a holiday (more demand). Either way, the shelf and the price tag are reacting to the tug-of-war.",
      "title": "Grocery Store Price Swings"
    },
    {
      "text": "You open a rideshare app after a concert and prices jump. Tons of riders request rides at once, but there aren’t enough drivers nearby, so the cost climbs until enough people decide to wait or walk.",
      "title": "Rideshare Surge After Events"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your favorite sneakers sell out in minutes, then show up online for double. A limited release meets a flood of buyers, so availability disappears fast and the going price gets pushed up.",
      "title": "Limited-Drop Sneakers"
    },
    {
      "text": "You try booking a flight for Thanksgiving and it’s way pricier than a random Tuesday. Airlines know more people want the same dates, so tickets get scarce and prices rise to match the crowd.",
      "title": "Holiday Travel Prices"
    },
    {
      "text": "When a new phone launches, the first weeks can mean long lines or backorders. Early hype brings lots of buyers, while stores and factories can’t instantly stock enough, so the market feels “tight.”",
      "title": "New Tech Launch Shortages"
    },
    {
      "text": "You sign a lease and notice rents vary by neighborhood. If lots of people want to live near downtown but there aren’t many units available, landlords can charge more and places get snapped up fast.",
      "title": "Rent in Popular Areas"
    },
    {
      "text": "After a storm warning, bottled water and plywood vanish. Stores didn’t plan for a sudden rush, so the same inventory gets spread across more shoppers—until restocks arrive and things calm down.",
      "title": "Storm Prep Runs"
    },
    {
      "text": "You try to get Taylor Swift tickets and they’re gone instantly. A huge fan base meets a fixed number of seats, so prices jump in resale markets where the “real” going rate gets discovered.",
      "title": "Concert Ticket Frenzy"
    },
    {
      "text": "A coffee shop raises wages to hire more baristas when they’re short-staffed. If fewer people want the job at the old pay, businesses often increase pay or perks until enough workers say yes.",
      "title": "Wages for Hard-to-Fill Jobs"
    },
    {
      "text": "You list a used bike online and get ten messages in an hour—so you bump the price. If it sits for weeks, you discount it. Selling your own stuff is a mini market where interest and availability set the deal.",
      "title": "Selling Stuff on Marketplace"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Ever used “folders within folders” on your laptop? Expanding a folder, then a subfolder, then another—same action repeated at smaller and smaller levels. That nested feeling is recursion showing up in a place you click every day.",
      "title": "Folders inside folders"
    },
    {
      "text": "Think of those Russian nesting dolls: open one, and there’s a smaller one with the same shape inside. It’s a physical “same thing, but smaller” pattern you can hold in your hand—basically recursion as a toy.",
      "title": "Russian nesting dolls"
    },
    {
      "text": "Zoom in on a fern leaf or Romanesco broccoli. The tiny pieces look like mini versions of the whole plant. Nature loves repeating a pattern at different scales, so you can spot recursion in your produce aisle.",
      "title": "Ferns and Romanesco broccoli"
    },
    {
      "text": "Standing between two mirrors, you see your reflection repeat into the distance—an image inside an image inside an image. It feels like visual recursion, where the scene contains a smaller version of itself again and again.",
      "title": "Mirror “infinite hallway”"
    },
    {
      "text": "In graphic design and animation, fractal-style art uses a motif that repeats as you zoom in. That trippy poster background or music visualizer isn’t random—it's a recursive pattern made visible.",
      "title": "Fractal art and visuals"
    },
    {
      "text": "At work, org charts often repeat: each manager has a team, and each team might have subteams with the same structure. Browsing it feels like walking a repeating pattern down levels of the company.",
      "title": "Org charts and team trees"
    },
    {
      "text": "Family trees and comment threads both branch the same way: a person has children, who have children; a comment has replies, which have replies. Scrolling through nested replies is like exploring a recursive structure.",
      "title": "Family trees and replies"
    },
    {
      "text": "When you play a strategy game and open a “world map,” then a region, then a city, then a building—each view is a smaller version of exploring. Many games are built around that repeated zoom-in pattern.",
      "title": "Games with maps within maps"
    },
    {
      "text": "In cooking, a stuffed dish can be “food inside food”: dumplings, stuffed peppers, turducken. The idea of a wrapper containing a smaller version of “a meal” is a fun, edible echo of recursion.",
      "title": "Stuffed foods and dumplings"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you’ve ever taught someone to search a messy room: “Check each box; if you find another box inside, check that too.” That real-life instruction naturally repeats itself, like a recursive approach to finding something.",
      "title": "Searching nested boxes"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Você entra no mercado com fome e, do nada, tudo parece mais “necessário”. Promoções e embalagens chamativas empurram escolhas rápidas — e você sai com itens que nem estavam na lista.",
      "title": "No supermercado, com pressa"
    },
    {
      "text": "“Só hoje: 70% OFF!” Mesmo sem precisar, você sente que está perdendo uma chance única. A sensação de urgência muda seu julgamento e faz o desconto parecer mais valioso do que é.",
      "title": "Promoções e sensação de urgência"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você lê 20 avaliações, mas uma reclamação muito intensa fica grudada na mente e pesa mais do que o resto. A compra vira “arriscada” por causa de uma história marcante.",
      "title": "Avaliações online que te influenciam"
    },
    {
      "text": "Uma discussão começa e você só lembra das vezes em que a outra pessoa “sempre faz isso”. A mente seleciona exemplos que sustentam sua impressão do momento, e o diálogo fica mais difícil.",
      "title": "Brigas de casal e “sempre/nunca”"
    },
    {
      "text": "Seu amigo diz “todo mundo vai” e, mesmo sem vontade, você topa. Quando parece que a maioria já decidiu, seguir junto dá uma sensação de segurança.",
      "title": "Pressão do grupo em rolês"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você vê um vídeo curto e sente que entendeu o assunto inteiro. A confiança sobe rápido, mesmo com pouca informação — e aí você compartilha antes de checar.",
      "title": "Redes sociais e certezas rápidas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você escolhe um candidato e, a partir daí, notícias que criticam parecem “tendenciosas”, enquanto as que elogiam parecem “claras”. A política vira torcida com facilidade.",
      "title": "Política como time de futebol"
    },
    {
      "text": "Depois de um dia ruim, uma resposta seca no WhatsApp vira “ela está brava comigo”. O humor do momento colore a leitura de mensagens neutras.",
      "title": "WhatsApp e interpretações"
    },
    {
      "text": "O primeiro preço que você vê vira referência. Se aparece “de R$ 299 por R$ 179”, o segundo parece ótimo — mesmo sem você saber quanto aquilo costuma custar.",
      "title": "Preços âncora em lojas e apps"
    },
    {
      "text": "Você termina uma série e acha que “sempre soube” quem era o vilão. Depois que acontece, a mente reorganiza a memória para parecer que era óbvio desde o início.",
      "title": "Séries e o “eu já sabia”"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Te recetan antibióticos y te dicen “termina el tratamiento”. Ahí está la selección natural: algunas bacterias aguantan mejor el medicamento y son las que quedan para multiplicarse después.",
      "title": "Antibióticos y bacterias tercas"
    },
    {
      "text": "En el hospital, esas noticias sobre “bacterias resistentes” no son ciencia ficción. En salas con mucho uso de desinfectantes y antibióticos, los microbios que toleran mejor ese ambiente se vuelven más comunes.",
      "title": "La resistencia en hospitales"
    },
    {
      "text": "En agricultura, cuando un herbicida ya “no hace efecto”, suele ser porque las malezas que sobrevivían por casualidad fueron dejando más semillas. Con los años, el campo se llena de las que resisten.",
      "title": "Malezas que ya no mueren"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tu repelente favorito puede fallar con el tiempo. Si algunos mosquitos sobreviven al insecticida y son los que tienen más crías, en tu colonia terminas viendo más mosquitos “difíciles de matar”.",
      "title": "Mosquitos vs. insecticidas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ese perro con hocico chato o el gato de pelo largo existen porque, generación tras generación, los humanos eligieron criar a los que tenían esos rasgos. Es selección, solo que con “criterio humano”.",
      "title": "Mascotas y cría selectiva"
    },
    {
      "text": "En redes ves fotos de polillas claras u oscuras en distintas ciudades. En zonas con troncos más oscuros (por hollín o sombra), las que se camuflan mejor suelen pasar desapercibidas más seguido.",
      "title": "Camuflaje en la ciudad"
    },
    {
      "text": "En una isla o valle aislado, un pico un poquito más fuerte o una lengua más larga puede marcar la diferencia para comer. Con pocas opciones de alimento, esos rasgos pueden volverse la norma en el lugar.",
      "title": "Islas: comida difícil, rasgos útiles"
    },
    {
      "text": "Después de una sequía o una helada fuerte, notas que ciertas plantas del jardín “aguantaron” y otras no. Si las sobrevivientes son las que más semillas dejan, el jardín cambia solo con el tiempo.",
      "title": "Tu jardín tras una sequía"
    },
    {
      "text": "En refugios y colonias de animales, a veces se nota quién se aparea más o quién llega a reproducirse. No es “el más fuerte”: puede ser el más discreto, el que canta mejor o el que evita peleas.",
      "title": "Cortejo y parejas en la naturaleza"
    },
    {
      "text": "En el supermercado, las frutas grandes y dulces dominan porque se cultivan más. Detrás de esa manzana perfecta hay generaciones de elegir y propagar plantas con los rasgos que la gente compra.",
      "title": "La manzana “perfecta” del súper"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "When you type a text and your phone finishes the sentence, that “next word” suggestion is ML quietly guessing what you meant to say.",
      "title": "Your phone’s next-word guesses"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ever search “sneak…” and instantly see “sneakers near me”? Search engines use ML to predict the query you’re heading toward and which results you’ll find useful.",
      "title": "Search that reads your mind"
    },
    {
      "text": "That “Because you watched…” row on Netflix/YouTube isn’t random. ML helps decide what to put in front of you so you’ll actually press play.",
      "title": "Streaming recommendations"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your social feed is a personalized highlight reel. ML helps pick which posts, creators, and ads show up first based on what you pause on, like, or skip.",
      "title": "What your feed shows you"
    },
    {
      "text": "Email that lands in Spam (or doesn’t) is often filtered by ML. It’s why obvious scams get blocked while a normal receipt usually goes straight to your inbox.",
      "title": "Spam filters in your inbox"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your bank flagging “Is this you?” on a purchase is ML watching for patterns that don’t match your usual spending—like a sudden charge in a new country.",
      "title": "Fraud alerts on your card"
    },
    {
      "text": "“Your ride is 6 minutes away” and the price surge during rush hour rely on ML-style forecasting—predicting demand, traffic, and arrival times from past patterns.",
      "title": "Maps and ride-share ETAs"
    },
    {
      "text": "Face unlock and automatic photo grouping (like “People” albums) use ML to recognize faces so you can search your camera roll by person.",
      "title": "Face unlock & photo albums"
    },
    {
      "text": "“Hey Siri/Alexa/Google…” works because ML helps turn messy real speech into text. That’s why it improves with accents, background noise, and new phrases.",
      "title": "Voice assistants hearing you"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your phone camera deciding “Night mode” or sharpening a blurry shot is ML doing behind-the-scenes photo enhancement—so pictures look better than what the lens captured.",
      "title": "Camera “magic” enhancements"
    },
    {
      "text": "When a store app suggests your size, a product you might like, or the “people also bought” section, that’s ML nudging you toward the most likely choice.",
      "title": "Online shopping suggestions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Those “I’m not a robot” puzzles and invisible bot checks often use ML to tell humans from automated scripts—especially when behavior looks suspicious.",
      "title": "CAPTCHAs and bot detection"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "That savings account you “barely check” is quietly stacking growth on top of past growth. Even small auto-transfers can start to feel like they’re gaining momentum—like a snowball that’s finally rolling downhill.",
      "title": "Your savings account snowball"
    },
    {
      "text": "Put money into a 401(k) or IRA early, and the oldest dollars often do the most work. It can feel unfair: two people invest the same amount, but the one who started sooner ends up way ahead.",
      "title": "Starting retirement early"
    },
    {
      "text": "Only paying the minimum on a credit card? The balance can start breeding more balance. Purchases from months ago keep “echoing” into today because the debt grows on top of what was already added.",
      "title": "Credit card minimum payments"
    },
    {
      "text": "Student loans, car loans, buy-now-pay-later—anything with interest can compound the pain if it runs long enough. A small rate difference can become a big dollar difference when years stack up.",
      "title": "Loans that quietly get heavier"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your home’s value rising 3–5% a year doesn’t just add up—it builds on prior gains. That’s why long time spans can turn “boring appreciation” into a huge chunk of net worth.",
      "title": "Home prices over decades"
    },
    {
      "text": "Missed payments and fees can trigger a chain reaction: late fee, higher rate, bigger next bill. It’s compounding’s darker cousin—little penalties that multiply into a bigger mess.",
      "title": "Late fees piling on"
    },
    {
      "text": "Those 1–2% fund fees don’t look scary—until they shave your gains year after year. It’s like a leak in a bucket: small now, surprisingly big over a long investing lifetime.",
      "title": "Investment fees eating returns"
    },
    {
      "text": "In a business, reinvesting profits can create compounding: more inventory, more marketing, more sales, more profit. It’s why “we’re not taking much out yet” can be a smart growth phase.",
      "title": "Reinvesting in a side hustle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Learning a bit each week compounds too. A few extra skills—spreadsheets, negotiating, coding—can stack into better jobs and higher pay, because each new skill builds on the last.",
      "title": "Skills that stack over time"
    },
    {
      "text": "On social media or YouTube, small audience growth can suddenly explode once sharing kicks in. More viewers brings more shares, which brings more viewers—compounding attention in real time.",
      "title": "Followers and viral growth"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Quando você respira fundo num parque ou numa rua arborizada, está sentindo um efeito direto da fotossíntese. Aquele “ar fresco” em áreas verdes acontece porque muitas folhas estão trabalhando ao mesmo tempo.",
      "title": "Ar “mais puro” no parque"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sabe a sensação de calor ao entrar num bairro sem árvores? Áreas com vegetação tendem a ser mais frescas porque plantas ajudam a umidificar o ar e a segurar parte do aquecimento do sol. É fotossíntese moldando o microclima.",
      "title": "Sombra e frescor das árvores"
    },
    {
      "text": "O arroz do prato, o feijão, a salada, as frutas: quase toda sua comida vem, direta ou indiretamente, de plantas que cresceram graças à fotossíntese. Até o bife “comeu fotossíntese” via pasto e ração.",
      "title": "O que tem no seu prato"
    },
    {
      "text": "No mercado, quando você vê “da época”, está vendo fotossíntese em ação. Sol, chuva e temperatura mudam a produtividade das plantações, e isso aparece no preço e na qualidade de frutas e verduras.",
      "title": "Preço e safra no supermercado"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pensa no pão, no macarrão, no óleo de soja. Esses alimentos dependem de grandes lavouras que precisam de muita luz e manejo. No campo, prever sol e nuvens é quase prever quanto a fotossíntese vai render.",
      "title": "Agricultura e grandes colheitas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em estufas e hortas indoor, lâmpadas roxas/rosadas ficam acesas por horas. Não é estética: é gente tentando dar às plantas a “luz certa” para crescerem bem, especialmente quando falta sol.",
      "title": "Estufas com luz artificial"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aquele aquário com plantas ou o lago da praça parecem só decoração, mas ali tem fotossíntese alimentando a cadeia toda. Plantinhas e algas sustentam microrganismos, peixes e outros seres no mesmo “mini-ecossistema”.",
      "title": "Aquário, lago e vida na água"
    },
    {
      "text": "Quando aparece notícia de “floração de algas” e água esverdeada, tem fotossíntese envolvida. Em excesso, algas mudam a qualidade da água e podem afetar peixes, cheiro e até o uso para lazer e abastecimento.",
      "title": "Água verde e algas no noticiário"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em debates sobre clima, reflorestamento e desmatamento, a fotossíntese está no centro. Menos vegetação significa menos captura de CO₂ e menos equilíbrio nos ecossistemas — algo que vira fumaça, seca e calor no dia a dia.",
      "title": "Clima, florestas e CO₂"
    },
    {
      "text": "Correr, pedalar, dançar: sua energia vem do alimento, que veio de plantas (ou de animais que comeram plantas). É como se a luz do sol tivesse virado “combustível” e chegado até seus músculos por uma longa trilha.",
      "title": "Energia para seu corpo se mexer"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Cuando mandas un “te veo a las 7” por WhatsApp o Signal, la encriptación va pegada al mensaje como un sobre sellado: aunque alguien lo intercepte, no lo puede leer.",
      "title": "Tus chats diarios"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ese candadito al pagar en una tienda online o meter tu dirección en un formulario es encriptación trabajando en silencio para que tus datos no viajen “en abierto” por la red.",
      "title": "Compras y pagos en línea"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando entras a tu banco desde el celular, la encriptación protege saldos, transferencias y claves. Es como hablar con el cajero en una cabina privada, no a gritos en la calle.",
      "title": "La app de tu banco"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tu Wi‑Fi de casa con contraseña (WPA2/WPA3) usa encriptación para que el vecino no pueda “escuchar” lo que navegas. Sin eso, la red sería como una conversación en altavoz.",
      "title": "La contraseña del Wi‑Fi"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando guardas fotos en iCloud, Google Drive o Dropbox, la encriptación ayuda a que, si alguien accede al almacenamiento, no encuentre tus archivos como si fueran carpetas abiertas.",
      "title": "Tus archivos en la nube"
    },
    {
      "text": "Al desbloquear tu iPhone/Android, el cifrado del dispositivo protege lo que hay dentro si lo pierdes. Sin tu PIN/huella, el teléfono es más parecido a una caja fuerte cerrada.",
      "title": "Si pierdes el celular"
    },
    {
      "text": "En un Zoom/Meet, la encriptación protege la llamada para que no sea fácil “colarse” a escuchar. Especialmente útil si hablas de trabajo, salud o temas personales.",
      "title": "Videollamadas y reuniones"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando guardas contraseñas en un gestor (1Password, Bitwarden, etc.), la encriptación mantiene tu “bóveda” cerrada. Así, una sola clave abre todo, y lo demás queda protegido.",
      "title": "Gestores de contraseñas"
    },
    {
      "text": "En tu trabajo, enviar contratos, bases de clientes o nóminas suele implicar archivos encriptados o correos protegidos. Es la diferencia entre mandar un documento o mandarlo en una caja con candado.",
      "title": "Documentos del trabajo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tus tarjetas sin contacto y apps de pago (NFC) usan encriptación para que el cobro no sea un número de tarjeta “a la vista”. Es como dar un token temporal en vez de tu tarjeta real.",
      "title": "Pagos con tap (NFC)"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "You set the AC to 72°F, the room warms up, and the system kicks on. When it cools back down, it eases off. That constant “too warm/too cool” adjustment is a loop you live with every day.",
      "title": "Your thermostat at home"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your phone suggests videos similar to what you watched. You watch more, so it suggests even more of the same. Before you know it, your feed feels like it’s “learning you” in real time.",
      "title": "Social media recommendations"
    },
    {
      "text": "A bank run is a classic loop: rumors trigger withdrawals, withdrawals create real trouble, and that trouble fuels more rumors. It’s a scary way beliefs can reshape reality fast.",
      "title": "Panic in financial markets"
    },
    {
      "text": "You drink coffee to feel alert, then sleep worse, then need more coffee the next day. Or you sleep well, feel better, and make choices that help you sleep again. Habits often build loops on loops.",
      "title": "Your energy and sleep routine"
    },
    {
      "text": "In a group chat, one person starts venting, others pile on, and the mood spirals. Or someone cracks a joke and the whole vibe lightens. Team emotions can reinforce themselves quickly.",
      "title": "Mood contagion in groups"
    },
    {
      "text": "When a room is packed, more people outside want in (“It must be great!”). The line gets longer, which attracts even more people. Popularity feeds on visible popularity.",
      "title": "Lines outside a hot new place"
    },
    {
      "text": "A little traffic slows cars, which creates braking, which creates more slowdown behind it. Sometimes it clears; other times it snowballs into a phantom jam with no obvious cause.",
      "title": "Traffic waves on highways"
    },
    {
      "text": "Predators and prey influence each other: more prey can support more predators; more predators reduce prey, which later reduces predators too. Nature often runs on these back-and-forth cycles.",
      "title": "Predator–prey in ecosystems"
